sec.p:
After 30 min calculation of continuous phase, 8,000 particles were injected and uniformly distributed in zone 1. The initial velocity of particle was set to be 0. The discrete phase was calculated at 29 min. Two kinds of discrete phase boundary (not including inlet and outlet) are discussed as the following:


The discrete phase boundary 1 was assumed to be perfectly rebound boundary on wall and roof boundaries. The trap boundary was applied on the floor boundary;

The discrete phase boundary 2 was assumed to be trap boundary on all surfaces.

Figure 6 shows the outdoor distribution of virus particles. The main conclusions are:


The virus particles begin to disperse to outdoors from the window of zone 2 at t = 50 s. With the increase of time, buildings B and C are in the high concentration area of virus and the area increases;

For the case studied, buildings D and E are safe and buildings A, B and C would be hazardous. The highest virus concentration area was close to building A;

The wind flow controls the transportation of virus, which is an effective way to control virus spread.

Fig. 6.
(a) and (b) represent the particle distribution at the cross-section plane with a height z = 3/5H and the outdoor particle distribution around buildings at different times. (1a, b) t = 50 s, (2a, b) t = 100 s, (3a, b) t = 150 s, (4a, b) t = 200, (5a, b) t = 250 s (6a, b) t = 300 s.
